You can use following to compare if they are equal using `GSON` lib

```
public static boolean comparePOJO(Object obj1, Object obj2) {
    return new Gson().toJson(obj1).equals(new Gson().toJson(obj2));
}
```

You can compare all fields in two objects of the same class with the help of [getDeclaredFields](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/Class.html#getDeclaredFields--)

```java
public static &lt;T&gt; boolean compareObjects(T obj1, T obj2) throws IllegalAccessException {
    if (obj1 == null || obj2 == null || !obj1.getClass().equals(obj2.getClass())) {
        return false;
    }

    Field[] fields = obj1.getClass().getDeclaredFields();
    for (Field field : fields) {
        Object value1 = field.get(obj1);
        Object value2 = field.get(obj2);
        if (value1 == null &amp;&amp; value2 != null || value1 != null &amp;&amp; !value1.equals(value2)) {
            return false;
        }
    }

    return true;
}
```
Alternatively make this as the `equals` function of your specific class.

Since you are only checking the equality of the data, I wouldn&#39;t recommend overriding _equals_.  
This is typically used to determine object equality, which is a slightly different context.

Just create a separate procedure.

An optimal approach, considering the database will have numerous values, would be to create a class to implement the procedure.  
This will allow for the re-use of the variables during iterative invocations, thus reducing memory consumption.

In this example I created a class, _UserEventUtil_, with a single method, _checkEquality_.  
It utilizes _[reflection](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/reflect/)_ to compare the opposing fields.

This should improve the scalability, and hence remove the requirement to explicitly type every field.

If you have any objects other than the basic _scalar_ types here, you can just add them to the _if-conditional_ checks, utilizing whatever data they may have to prove equality.

```java
import java.lang.reflect.Field;

public class UserEventUtil {
    UserEvent userEventA, userEventB;
    Field[] fieldsA, fieldsB;
    Field fieldA, fieldB;
    Class&lt;?&gt; type;
    String stringA, stringB;
    int index;

    public UserEventUtil(UserEvent userEventA, UserEvent userEventB) {
        this.userEventA = userEventA;
        this.userEventB = userEventB;
    }

    boolean checkEquality() throws IllegalAccessException {
        fieldsA = userEventA.getClass().getDeclaredFields();
        fieldsB = userEventB.getClass().getDeclaredFields();
        for (index = 0; index &lt; fieldsA.length; index++) {
            fieldA = fieldsA[index];
            fieldB = fieldsB[index];
            type = fieldA.getType();
            if (type == String.class) {
                stringA = (String) fieldA.get(userEventA);
                stringB = (String) fieldB.get(userEventB);
                if (stringA == null &amp;&amp; stringB == null) continue;
                if (stringA == null || stringB == null) return false;
                else if (!stringA.equals(stringB)) return false;
            } else if (type == int.class) {
                if (fieldA.getInt(userEventA) != fieldB.getInt(userEventB))
                    return false;
            } else if (type == float.class) {
                if (fieldA.getFloat(userEventA) != fieldB.getFloat(userEventB))
                    return false;
            }
        }
        return true;
    }
}
```

